Take a 2.2-inch by 4.9-inch (5.5-cm by 12.5-cm) sheet of chiyogami paper and double fold the shorter end to create a ridge. This sheet of paper will form the kimono, and this ridge or edge will become the collar of the kimono. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/7\/72\/Make-Hina-Matsuri-Dolls-Step-4Bullet1.jpg\/v4-460px-Make-Hina-Matsuri-Dolls-Step-4Bullet1.jpg","bigUrl":"\/images\/thumb\/7\/72\/Make-Hina-Matsuri-Dolls-Step-4Bullet1.jpg\/aid5283343-v4-728px-Make-Hina-Matsuri-Dolls-Step-4Bullet1.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":"728","bigHeight":"546","licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/creativecommons.org\/licenses\/by-nc-sa\/3.0\/\">Creative Commons<\/a><br>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p><\/div>"}

Flip the paper so that it is wrong-side up. Fold 0.4-inch (1-cm) of the short end up. If the paper pattern has a top and bottom, do this at the top of the paper. {"smallUrl":"https:\/\/www.wikihow.com\/images\/thumb\/7\/79\/Make-Hina-Matsuri-Dolls-Step-4Bullet2.jpg\/v4-460px-Make-Hina-Matsuri-Dolls-Step-4Bullet2.jpg","bigUrl":"\/images\/thumb\/7\/79\/Make-Hina-Matsuri-Dolls-Step-4Bullet2.jpg\/aid5283343-v4-728px-Make-Hina-Matsuri-Dolls-Step-4Bullet2.jpg","smallWidth":460,"smallHeight":345,"bigWidth":"728","bigHeight":"546","licensing":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p>License: <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https:\/\/creativecommons.org\/licenses\/by-nc-sa\/3.0\/\">Creative Commons<\/a><br>\n<\/p><p><br \/>\n<\/p><\/div>"}

Flip the paper back over to the front. Fold 0.2-inch (0.5-cm) from your previous fold back over to the front, creating a raised edge.
